data.content:
## Analysis

Your code has three Thread.Abort-related APIs that **throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8**:

| API | Location | Pattern |
|-----|----------|---------|
| `_workerThread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Cancellable work loop |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `ProcessLoop()` | Cleanup on abort |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | `ProcessLoop()` | Continue loop after abort |

The core shift: .NET Framework could forcibly inject an exception into a running thread. .NET 8 **cannot** — you must use cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking call can wake up
                ProcessItem(item);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed; the while-loop condition handles continuation.
                // Loop exits naturally because token.IsCancellationRequested is true.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish cleanly (replaces Thread.Sleep + Abort)
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `volatile bool _running` | `CancellationTokenSource` | Token integrates with blocking APIs; a bool cannot wake a blocked thread |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Cooperative signal instead of forcible injection |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` | The `when` filter avoids catching unrelated OCEs |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No auto-rethrow — `OperationCanceledException` is a normal exception |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` | `_workerThread.Join(2s)` | Actually waits for the thread instead of sleeping blindly |
| *(nothing)* | `IDisposable` | `CancellationTokenSource` holds timer/callback resources that must be released |

## Critical Pitfall: `GetNextItem()` Must Accept the Token

The biggest migration risk is the blocking `GetNextItem()` call. With `Thread.Abort`, the runtime forcibly interrupted it. **Cooperative cancellation can't do that** — if `GetNextItem()` blocks forever, `Cancel()` has no effect until the call returns.

You **must** thread the token through:

```csharp
// If backed by a BlockingCollection<T>:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // wakes up on cancellation
}

// If backed by a synchronous wait (e.g., ManualResetEvent):
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Replace: _signal.WaitOne();
    WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return DequeueItem();
}

// If backed by raw Thread.Sleep polling:
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    while (!HasWork())
    {
        // Replace: Thread.Sleep(500);
        token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(500); // wakes on cancel OR timeout
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    }
    return DequeueItem();
}
```

If `GetNextItem` calls code you **cannot modify** (third-party, native), move it to a child process and use `Process.Kill` as the last-resort termination mechanism.

## Summary Checklist

- ✅ `Thread.Abort()` → `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()`
- ✅ `ThreadAbortException` → `OperationCanceledException`
- ✅ `Thread.ResetAbort()` → removed (not needed)
- ✅ Cleanup logic (`RollbackCurrentTransaction`) preserved in catch
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` disposed via `IDisposable`
- ⚠️ **You must update `GetNextItem` to accept and honor the token** — this is the one place the migration can silently fail at runtime
